A BAD TRIP LEADS ANNIE, OUR EARNEST HEROINE, THROUGH A JOURNEY OF SUFFERING AND SELF-DISCOVERY. 

Caught within the confines of her own mind, Annie struggles against the doubled weight of trauma and despair. In order to crawl her way out, she must grapple with the cruelest parts of her psyche, and make peace with her inner child and suppressed past. Annie argues with her demons and punches her way toward the light, with a little help from her dedicated and loving friends. 

Lushly illustrated with influences from spiritual iconography and psychedelic imagery, Halbert crafts an unflinching yet compassionate story about pain, rage, and the blessings we can give ourselves.

128 full-color pages; 8” x 10” hardcover; SRP: $29.99 contains 18+ material

Absolutely loved it. Know not everyone digs Guillermo del Toro’s movies, but I tend to love them. What can I say, I’m a big ol’ softie. It’s an incredible feat of stop-motion animation and filmmaking. Pinocchio’s world is full of gorgeous colors, vibrant textures and impeccable lighting. It’s exploding with exquisitely designed characters full of heart. Delightfully matched with a delicate soundtrack. Everyone’s voice acting is pure magic and Ewan McGregor as the cricket and narrator was a particular favorite. How inspiring. 🪵🦗👴🏻🐒

Wow! What a way to end the year 💜📚💜 Sincere gratitude to Clark Burscough and @sally_madden for both giving ACID NUN a shout out on their @the_comics_journal_ Best Comics of 2022 lists! Check out the full article and bask in the glow of some of the truly outstanding work that came out in 2022. I also wanted to take a moment to say thank you to anybody who supported my art or showed me any love over the past 12 months. It means the world to me and helps me to keep moving forward with that fire burning brightly inside ❤️🙏❤️ I was thrilled to be on Ryan Carey’s Four Color Apocalypse top ten list for best collected editions, @josephaziemba’s fave five graphic novels/comic collections first read in 2022 and was utterly blown away to see ACID NUN receive an honorable mention on @publisherswkly 2022 Graphic Novel Critics Poll. I worked really hard on this book and put everything I had into it. Love, blood, sweat and tears. It’s a really great feeling to know my efforts have been appreciated and I’m incredibly excited for what’s to come. Working with one of the best small press publishers around has been one of the coolest experiences of my life. Endless gratitude to @silversprocket with special regard for Avi, Ari and Carina 🐐💕🐐 Sending you all so much love and wishing everyone a glorious 2023 filled with joy, fun and beautiful connections with your loved ones. In love and lightness 😘🌞❤️‍🔥

Never going on vacation again 😱 Infinity Pool is a ripper. Unfortunately the NC17 cut isn’t being played in theaters, will have to stream it when it becomes available. In terms of filmmaking, it’s truly stunning to look at. Loved the masks, exotic drugs and wild sex romps. The story was a bit too disjointed for me to ever fully buy in to the madness. I do wish the script had been a bit tighter and they cut out some of the redundant characters. (Spoiler) Mia Goth on top of the car with fried chicken and wine, berating AS, was downright iconic. Skarsgård gives one hell of a performance and really goes through it. A must see 💀🩸

It is with a heavy heart that I share some news. As many of you know, Scott and I have been best friends and partners for the past 8 years and married since 2017. We've made the difficult decision to part ways. It is both mutual and amicable and we gave tremendous efforts to try to reach a different outcome. Ultimately, we've decided separating is the best and healthiest decision for both of us and our individual happiness. I'm a bit scared, as I have no idea where I'm going to live or what this new chapter will look like. But such is life and I'm incredibly fortunate to have a loving family and solid network of support. I may reach out to folks as I figure out my living situation. I'll always admire Scott and do not regret anything. He's a wonderful person and I've been lucky to share my life with him for nearly a decade. Thank you in advance for your patience and understanding.

It’s hard for me to believe that it’s been four years without you here, Finbar. I remember this day so vividly, it was the last time we saw each other. You had a light so bright, it shone outward for miles. Thank you for being my stepdad and always making me feel safe, protected and so loved. We were great friends and had a mutual respect for each others creativity and work ethic. We shared so many enormous laughs together, you were insanely funny. And one of a kind… I’ve never met anyone quite like you, before entering my life or since. The world got dimmer when you left us. I’ll always love you and dream of a day we can see each other again. I cherish every, single, memory. Rest easy, Finius ❤️

I’m beyond thrilled to share the news about VISCERE #1 Body Horror, to be published Oct 2023 via @stregasporca! 💀👄💀 Brought to you by the brilliant mind of @skellyskellyskelly ⛓️⚰️⛓️ Check out my story, TOTAL VORE if ya snag a copy! I went all out on it🩸🍽️🩸 The artists in this anthology are AMAZING 😍😭😍 I’m honored to have my work included. Here are a few words from the Kickstarter campaign page:

“Strega Sporca, a new comics publishing imprint by Katie Skelly, is proud to announce the upcoming release of its debut title: Viscere #1: Body Horror, a comics anthology that explores the world of body horror through transgressive genre stories. Featuring the work of eight emerging artists, the anthology delves into topics ranging from plastic surgery gone wrong to doppelgängers run amuck, ultimately asking readers to have a good think about the flesh they call home.

The anthology showcases the ruthless talents of Tia Roxae, Coco Paluck, Natalia Hernandez, Chloe Brailsford, Jenna Cha, Rin Ascher, Alejandra Gutiérrez, and Corinne Halbert. Each artist brings a unique perspective and style to the stories they tell, with inspirations ranging from underground comics, manga, giallo, Eurosleaze, and more. These artists have created an incredible collection of stories that explore the complex relationship 
between the body and the self, and with your help we can bring them to the world.”

Thanks for looking and please back it if you can! Linkz in my story highlightz. Content warning: self harm, graphic violence, mutilation, and gore 💀🩸💀 #viscere #stregasporca #bodyhorror #comics #katieskelly

Beautiful Chicago friends! Some news I need to share with all of you. My time in this wonderful city is coming to an end. I've lived here for almost 18 years and have grown so much, had countless, incredible experiences and established some truly beautiful and lasting friendships. The time has come for me to mosey on... Forgive me if I don't disclose my plans at the moment, it's important to me to let my path forward unfold naturally and organically. The last big event I'll be attending will be @cakechicago on June 3rd and 4th 📚🍰📚 Please swing by my table (505B) and say hello! And goodbye 👋❤️😭 CAKE has always been very special to me, it's been my home show since 2014 and I'm glad to be returning this year with copies of ACID NUN in hand. Hope to see you there and much love to every last person who has shown me support, respect and kindness during my time here. Much love all 💕🦋🌞❤️

Getting a divorce really sucks. Whether it’s amicable or not, it’s a painful experience. It feels like parts of myself have died that will never come back. And it has forever changed me. Ultimately, hopefully for the better. We finalized everything this week and it’ll take some time for me to recover from this heartache. I want to thank everyone who has been there for me throughout this process, you know who you are. I’ll never forget your generous support and kindness. It’s really hard for me to reach out for help and I have a tendency to self isolate when emotionally overwhelmed. So had to go underground for a bit, to protect my heart. But slowly, over the course of the summer, I’ll be emerging from my chrysalis and am excited to begin work on some new projects, painting and comics related. Much love to all y’all out there that send me encouragement and good vibes. It really helps me keep moving forward. In times like this, it’s easy to feel defeated and want to give up. But that’s how you know it’s more important than ever to keep putting one foot in front of the other, gotta keep going. Love and magic surround all of us, even when we can’t see it. Much love everyone ❤️

Wow. That is the word I uttered out loud immediately upon finishing the total masterpiece that is Monica. Actually it was more like wow, wow, wow, wowwwwwww. In Clowe's own words, Monica is the story of a woman's life, from cradle to grave. But it's so much more than that. I was lucky enough to catch his talk @cartooncrossroads earlier this month, a deeply enriching and inspiring experience. One thing that really stuck out to me was his discussion of memory. He described a sensation of having memories of memories, that at this stage of his life, they have become distorted further and further over time. He also mentioned that after his mother passed, he really didn't have much family left, so all of these memories exist only in his own mind, no longer having anyone to corroborate any of these experiences from early life. There are so many vastly different entry points for me in this spectacular tome. Feelings of loss, loneliness, deep introspection into one's own life, being an outsider, loving your family members while simultaneously enduring the heavy weight of shared conflict and difficult emotions. Much like Patience, Monica's color palette is utterly beautiful. I lived with my grandparents growing up and they never updated their house. The kitchen was acid yellow, the tv room was brown and orange and my bedroom had dazzling pop flower wallpaper in stunning dayglo pinks, yellows, greens and blues. That vintage 1960s palette is forever burned in my heart and dna. Clowe's particular use of color tugs at my own distorted memory and comforts me deeply. Seven years in the making, you can feel every line, panel, word and color choice have been deeply considered. I absolutely adored it 📘🖤❤️‍🔥 @daniel_clowes @fantagraphics #danielclowes #monica #fantagraphics #comics #graphicnovel

It's quite the trip through festively fun lands reminiscent of Ren Faires and William Shakespeare plays. Every page is saturated with vibrant colors and visual decadence. My Grandpa Nick has been the rock of my life since I was a lil baby girl. It is truly a remarkable gift that I got to treasure his presence for over four decades. He passed away peacefully last night at the age of 98. He was a kind, funny, intelligent, warm, caring and hard working man. His loving and gregarious spirit was a joy to be around and we got along like peanut butter and jelly. He always made me laugh with his incredibly corny jokes. I owe much of my stability to him and will miss him every day. Thank you for everything, everyone whose life you touched was better for it ❤️

Forbidden Planet is closing out their 2023 Indie Creator Spotlight on Saturday December 9th from 5 to 7PM with one heck of a line up. We got three heavy hitters ready to both razzle and dazzle you with their combined creative output! Local comic legend Josh Bayer will be celebrating the release of the original graphic novel Unended, one of his most epic and personal pieces of work yet. Nick Forker just dropped the interactive tabletop gaming inspired Make Yourself A Hero as well as a brand new issue of his ongoing series Eyeland, which just so happens to have a cover by everyone’s favorite Nun obsessed artist Corinne Halbert, who also recently self published a zine of beautifully executed and totally psycho-delic Acid Nun paintings. So come by and meet these three unstoppable independent artists all with brand spanking new books, ready to inspire you to be the next creator spotlighted right here at Forbidden Planet NYC. 

Who: Josh Bayer, Nick Forker and Corinne Halbert 
What: Indie Creator Spotlight
When: Saturday December 9th 5-7PM
Where: Forbidden Planet NYC 832 Broadway NY, NY
Why: Support your local independent artist!

I started reading UNENDED on the NYC subway system, tearing up, which seems like the ideal way to read this work. @joshmbayer dives remarkably deep into memory, family history and the formative pain that only having a parent die in childhood and an emotionally unavailable father can forge. Bayer’s singular pulsating and surreal drawing style sets his story ablaze with electric currents. Dazzling ur eyeballs and sewing messages of loss and healing onto your heart. UNENDED will certainly be regarded as one of the best comics of 2023, get your hands on this important work. Come see Josh, @nicholasforker and myself this Sat, Dec 9th @forbiddenplanetnyc from 5-7. We’ll be signing books and celebrating the release of UNENDED 📚🖤📚 #joshbayer #uncivilizedbooks #unended #forbiddenplanetnyc #comics

POOR THINGS is a visual  Smörgåsbord jam packed with horny escapades and deep internal introspection. Every single outfit Emma Stone wears makes me want to scream 😱😍 The sleeves, my god, the gorgeous puffy sleeves 👗💞 Her performance is pure, awkward poetry in motion. Willem Dafoe knocks it outta the park as always, looking more like Frankenstein’s monster than beautiful Bella herself. And Mark Ruffalo devours his role of jealous lover and pretentious, over privileged prick. THE FAVOURITE walked so POOR THINGS could run. Love both films so much. Can’t wait to see what Yorgos Lanthimos does next 🎥⚡️💀 #emmastone #poorthings #willemdafoe
